{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/stock-market-and-bitcoin-price-relationship-python-analysis-f39f992201c7", "time": 1683003946.460999, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/stock-market-and-bitcoin-price-relationship-python-analysis-f39f992201c7/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Stock Market and Bitcoin Price Relationship \u2014 Python Analysis | by Jose Manu (CodingFun) | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Stock Market and Bitcoin Price Relationship \u2014 Python Analysis", "description": "We will be able to answer that question in this article through an analysis with Python and Pandas. First we will retrieve, using a free API, Bitcoin and stock prices for the last years. Then, we\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://financialmodelingprep.com/developer/docs/", "anchor_text": "financialmodelingprep", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%26P_500_Index", "anchor_text": "S&P 500 index", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://pandas-datareader.readthedocs.io/en/latest/", "anchor_text": "Pandas DataReader", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://fred.stlouisfed.org/", "anchor_text": "Federal Reserve Economic Data (FRED)", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://financialmodelingprep.com/developer/docs/", "anchor_text": "financialmodelingprep API", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://techtutorialsx.com/2016/10/30/python-parsing-json/", "anchor_text": "article", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.from_dict.html", "anchor_text": "pd.DataFrame.from_dict()", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.merge.html", "anchor_text": "Pandas merge documentation", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python-pandas-dataframe-corr/", "anchor_text": "dataframe.corr()", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.graphics.correlation.plot_corr.html", "anchor_text": "matplotlib and statsmodels", "paragraph_index": 19}], "all_paragraphs": ["We will be able to answer that question in this article through an analysis with Python and Pandas. First we will retrieve, using a free API, Bitcoin and stock prices for the last years. Then, we will calculate the correlation between the stock market and Bitcoin prices. Finally, we will conclude the analysis plotting the correlation through a correlation matrix graph.", "Since the appearance of Bitcoin, I have always wondered what is the role of Bitcoin in our economy. Below are three potential roles:", "In order to get data to carry out our analysis, I will use financialmodelingprep API to retrieve Bitcoin prices. They also offer free stock data available but in order to show you two different ways of getting data, I will use Pandas DataReader to retrieve stock data.", "As a proxy for our market data, we are going to use the S&P 500 index. The S&P 500 is an index that measures the stock performance of the 500 largest companies listed in the United States. We will use Pandas DataReader to download SP500 prices and Federal Reserve Economic Data (FRED) as the source.", "In case you have never used Pandas DataReader and Pandas before, you will need to install the packages. You can do that by using the pip command.", "Great, now we are ready to retrieve our data with Python. First, we will extract S&P500 stock prices for the last ten years. Note, that we can easily get the data in a Pandas Series that we call SP500 by using web.DataReader and specifying the series name (i.e. sp500) and the provider (i.e. fred)", "Above lines of code will return below S&P 500 Pandas Series containing S&P prices for the last 10 years:", "Let\u2019s now retrieve Bitcoin prices. For that, we will use financialmodelingprep API. We will make an http get request to the API end point that will return a dictionary containing historical BTC prices:", "We parse the dictionary included in the key name historical. If you are not familiar how to parse an API response, I recommend you to read the following article.", "Now, by looking into the content of the BTCUSD variable, we can see that BTCUSD is a list of dictionaries, and each element in the list is a different day containing Bitcoin prices. BTC prices are stored under the key close.", "For example, we see that on the 15th of February, the price of Bitcoin was $10,244.", "We need to convert the list of dictionaries into a Pandas DataFrame. We can easily do that using pd.DataFrame.from_dict():", "Finally, we have our BTC and S&P 500 prices in two Pandas DataFrames. Now, we only need to merge them together. Fortunately for us, this is very easy to do with Python and Pandas.", "We can use pd.merge to join both DataFrames on the index since index contains the date. Therefore, we want to join S&P500 and BTC prices on the matching day.", "We can pass as an argument right_index and left_index equal to True to let Pandas know that we want to use the index for merging. See the Pandas merge documentation for additional details.", "Great, we have our data ready for the analysis. Now, we can move on to find out how stock and Bitcoin prices relate to each other.", "For that, we can use pandas dataframe.corr() to find the correlation of our Pandas DataFrame columns:", "The values from a correlation matrix range from -1 to 1. Closer to +1 means that both variables move closely together and in the same direction. A value of 0 meaning that there is no relationship between the variables. Wile a negative correlation indicates that the variables move in different directions. The closer to -1 the stronger the inverse relationship.", "By looking into our results, we see that we have a strong and positive correlation of 0.83 between the price of Bitcoin and S&P 500. That means that when the prices of the stock market go up, we can expect Bitcoin to follow the trend and also move up.", "We can also visualize the correlation by using matplotlib and statsmodels:", "The red colour of the graph means that the relationship is strong and positive. We can also check if the relationship is statistically significant using linregress and scipy.stats:", "Since our p-value is lower than 0.05 we can reject H0, and therefore, we can statistically say that Bitcoin and stock prices are moving together.", "Using Python and Pandas, we have analysed the relationship between stock market and Bitcoin prices. As per our analysis results, we can say that BTC and S&P500 prices move along in the same direction.", "It would be interesting to know if this relationship holds as well in a recessionary business cycle. To perform such analysis we may need to wait a while since during the last years, we have been living in an expansionary economy.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Python for Finance. Learn step by step how to automate cool financial analysis tools."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff39f992201c7&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstock-market-and-bitcoin-price-relationship-python-analysis-f39f992201c7&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstock-market-and-bitcoin-price-relationship-python-analysis-f39f992201c7&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/sign